# Vite Dev Server

Vite's dev server provides instant startup and sub-millisecond HMR by serving source files as native ES modules. All server options live under the `server` key in [[vite/config]].

## Starting the Dev Server

```bash
# All three are equivalent
vite
vite dev
vite serve

# Common flags
vite --host 0.0.0.0      # expose to network
vite --port 3000         # custom port
vite --open              # open browser on start
vite --open /login       # open specific path
vite --force             # re-bundle dependencies
vite --strictPort        # fail if port is taken
```

## Configuring Host and Port

```typescript
// vite.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vite'

export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    host: '0.0.0.0',    // expose to all interfaces (default: 'localhost')
    port: 3000,          // default: 5173
    strictPort: true,    // fail if port in use (default: false — auto-increments)
    open: true,          // open browser on start
  }
})
```

Set `host: true` as shorthand for `0.0.0.0`. Required when running inside Docker, WSL2, or Codespaces to make the server reachable from the host machine.

## Proxy Configuration

Proxy API requests to a backend server during development. Uses [http-proxy](https://github.com/http-party/node-http-proxy) under the hood.

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    proxy: {
      // Simple: /api/users -> http://localhost:4000/api/users
      '/api': 'http://localhost:4000',

      // Rewrite path: /api/users -> http://localhost:4000/users
      '/api': {
        target: 'http://localhost:4000',
        changeOrigin: true,
        rewrite: (path) => path.replace(/^\/api/, ''),
      },

      // WebSocket proxy
      '/socket.io': {
        target: 'ws://localhost:4000',
        ws: true,
      },

      // Regex matching: /fallback/any/path -> http://localhost:4000/any/path
      '^/fallback/.*': {
        target: 'http://localhost:4000',
        changeOrigin: true,
        rewrite: (path) => path.replace(/^\/fallback/, ''),
      },

      // Secure backend with self-signed cert
      '/secure-api': {
        target: 'https://localhost:4443',
        secure: false,           // accept self-signed certs
        changeOrigin: true,
      },

      // Access the proxy instance for custom logic
      '/custom': {
        target: 'http://localhost:4000',
        configure: (proxy, options) => {
          proxy.on('proxyReq', (proxyReq, req, res) => {
            proxyReq.setHeader('X-Forwarded-For', req.socket.remoteAddress)
          })
        },
      },
    }
  }
})
```

Proxy rules only apply to the dev server. For production, configure your reverse proxy (nginx, Caddy) or API gateway.

## HMR Configuration

Hot Module Replacement updates modules in-place without a full page reload. It works automatically for CSS, Vue SFCs, React (with `@vitejs/plugin-react`), and Svelte.

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    hmr: {
      protocol: 'ws',        // 'ws' or 'wss' (default: auto-detected)
      host: 'localhost',     // HMR WebSocket host
      port: 5173,            // HMR WebSocket port (default: server port)
      clientPort: 443,       // port the browser connects to (for reverse proxies)
      overlay: true,         // show error overlay (default: true)
      timeout: 30000,        // connection timeout in ms
    }
  }
})
```

### HMR Troubleshooting

| Symptom | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| HMR not connecting | Check `server.hmr.host` and firewall rules; behind a reverse proxy, set `clientPort` |
| Full page reloads instead of HMR | Module lacks HMR boundary — check that framework plugin is installed ([[vite/plugins]]) |
| HMR slow on large projects | Use `server.warmup.clientFiles` to pre-transform hot paths |
| WebSocket blocked by proxy | Set `server.hmr.protocol: 'wss'` and `server.hmr.clientPort: 443` |
| Overlay covers app in production-like env | Set `server.hmr.overlay: false` |

To disable HMR entirely: `server.hmr: false`.

## HTTPS Setup

Enable TLS for local HTTPS development (required for testing Service Workers, Secure Cookies, and HTTP/2).

```typescript
import fs from 'node:fs'

export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    https: {
      key: fs.readFileSync('certs/localhost-key.pem'),
      cert: fs.readFileSync('certs/localhost-cert.pem'),
    }
  }
})
```

### Quick Self-Signed Certs with mkcert

```bash
# Install mkcert and create a local CA
brew install mkcert      # or: choco install mkcert / scoop install mkcert
mkcert -install

# Generate certs in your project
mkdir -p certs
mkcert -key-file certs/localhost-key.pem -cert-file certs/localhost-cert.pem localhost 127.0.0.1 ::1
```

Alternatively, use the `@vitejs/plugin-basic-ssl` plugin for zero-config self-signed certs:

```typescript
import basicSsl from '@vitejs/plugin-basic-ssl'

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [basicSsl()],
})
```

When HTTPS is enabled, Vite automatically upgrades to HTTP/2.

## Middleware Mode

Mount Vite as middleware in an existing Express, Connect, Koa, or Fastify server. Essential for custom SSR setups and complex backend integrations.

```typescript
import express from 'express'
import { createServer as createViteServer } from 'vite'

async function startServer() {
  const app = express()

  const vite = await createViteServer({
    server: { middlewareMode: true },
    appType: 'custom',          // disable built-in HTML serving
  })

  // Use Vite's connect-compatible middleware
  app.use(vite.middlewares)

  // Custom API routes
  app.get('/api/data', (req, res) => {
    res.json({ hello: 'world' })
  })

  // SSR: transform and render on every request
  app.use('*', async (req, res) => {
    const url = req.originalUrl
    const template = await vite.transformIndexHtml(url, 
      fs.readFileSync('index.html', 'utf-8'))
    const { render } = await vite.ssrLoadModule('/src/entry-server.tsx')
    const html = template.replace('<!--ssr-outlet-->', await render(url))
    res.status(200).set({ 'Content-Type': 'text/html' }).end(html)
  })

  app.listen(3000)
}
startServer()
```

In middleware mode, Vite does not start its own HTTP server or open a browser. Call `vite.close()` on shutdown to clean up.

## File System Restrictions

Vite restricts which files can be served to prevent accidental exposure of sensitive files outside the project.

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    fs: {
      strict: true,             // only serve files within allowed dirs (default: true)
      allow: [
        '/path/to/shared-lib',  // allow files outside project root
      ],
      deny: [
        '.env',                 // block specific patterns
        '.env.*',
        '*.pem',
        '**/.git/**',
      ],
    }
  }
})
```

By default `server.fs.allow` includes the project root, workspace root (if in a monorepo), and any symlinked dependencies. The `deny` list is checked before `allow` and defaults to blocking dotfiles.

## Warmup

Pre-transform frequently used modules at server start to avoid transformation waterfalls on first page load.

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    warmup: {
      clientFiles: [
        './src/main.tsx',
        './src/components/Layout.tsx',
        './src/pages/Home.tsx',
      ],
      ssrFiles: [
        './src/entry-server.tsx',
      ],
    }
  }
})
```

Accepts glob patterns: `./src/components/**/*.tsx`. Only warm up files that are actually imported early — warming too many files wastes startup time.

## CORS

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    cors: true,                       // default: allow all origins
    // or fine-grained:
    cors: {
      origin: 'http://localhost:3000',
      methods: ['GET', 'POST'],
      credentials: true,
    }
  }
})
```

## Custom Response Headers

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    headers: {
      'X-Custom-Header': 'value',
      'Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy': 'require-corp',
      'Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy': 'same-origin',
    }
  }
})
```

The `COEP` and `COOP` headers above enable `SharedArrayBuffer`, required by some WASM workloads.

## Allowed Hosts

Restrict which hostnames the dev server responds to, preventing DNS rebinding attacks:

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    allowedHosts: ['myapp.local', '.example.com'],  // dot prefix matches subdomains
  }
})
```

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| `HOST` | Override `server.host` from command line |
| `PORT` | Override `server.port` from command line |
| `HTTPS` | Enable HTTPS when set to a truthy value |

See [[vite/env]] for the full env variable system.

## Watch Options

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  server: {
    watch: {
      // Chokidar options
      usePolling: true,           // needed on network file systems / Docker bind mounts
      interval: 100,              // polling interval in ms
      ignored: ['**/coverage/**'], // additional ignore patterns
    }
  }
})
```

Set `usePolling: true` when file watching doesn't work (common in Docker with bind mounts, some NFS setups, and WSL2 cross-filesystem access).
